The Scoring System — Full Breakdown
Every task starts with a base score from its priority, then gains or loses points based on four more factors:

Factor	Points
LOW priority	10 pts (1 × 10)
MEDIUM priority	20 pts (2 × 10)
HIGH priority	40 pts (4 × 10)
URGENT priority	60 pts (6 × 10)
Overdue (past deadline)	+35 pts
Due today	+20 pts
Due in 1-2 days	+15 pts
Due this week (≤7 days)	+10 pts
No due date	+0 pts
Status = DONE	-50 pts
Status = REVIEW	-15 pts
Has blocker/critical/urgent tag	+8 pts
Updated today	+5 pts

Concrete Example
Task A: MEDIUM priority, due in 3 days, IN_PROGRESS, no tags
20 (medium) + 10 (due this week) + 0 + 0 = 30 points

Task B: LOW priority, overdue, tagged 'blocker'
10 (low) + 35 (overdue) + 0 + 8 (blocker) = 53 points

Task B ranks higher than Task A even though it's LOW priority — because being overdue with a blocker tag matters more than being MEDIUM with time to spare.

Key Insight: The any() Function
any(tag in ['blocker', 'critical', 'urgent'] for tag in task.tags)
This checks if AT LEAST ONE tag matches the special list. It stops checking the moment it finds one match — like asking 'does anyone here speak French?' and stopping as soon as one person raises their hand.

Understanding Questions & Answers
Q1: A task is URGENT and DONE — what is its score?
60 (urgent) - 50 (done) = 10 points
Very low — which makes sense. You don't want finished tasks appearing at the top even if they were urgent.

Q2: Why do overdue tasks get MORE points instead of less?
The algorithm is a helper, not a punishment system. Its job is to show what needs attention most urgently. An overdue task desperately needs attention — pushing it to the top makes practical sense.

Q3: What weight would you give a new CRITICAL priority level?
I'd give it 9. The gaps between levels increase as urgency rises: LOW→MEDIUM is +1, MEDIUM→HIGH is +2, HIGH→URGENT is +2. Following this pattern, URGENT→CRITICAL should be at least +3, making it 9. CRITICAL tasks would start at 90 points.

Prompt 2: Decipher Code with Unclear Intent
The Confusing Code
def sort_tasks_by_importance(tasks):
    task_scores = [(calculate_task_score(task), task) for task in tasks]
    sorted_tasks = [task for _, task in sorted(task_scores, key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)]
    return sorted_tasks

Better Variable Names
Current Name	Better Name
task_scores	tasks_with_scores
x	score_task_pair
_	ignored_score
sorted_tasks	tasks_by_priority

The Decorate-Sort-Undecorate Pattern
This is a classic three-step pattern:
•	DECORATE — attach a score to each task: [(80, TaskA), (53, TaskB)]
•	SORT — sort pairs by the score number, highest first
•	UNDECORATE — strip scores away, return just the tasks in order

Pseudocode — Plain English Version
FOR each task in tasks:
    calculate its importance score
    pair the score with the task → (score, task)

SORT all pairs by score, highest first

EXTRACT just the tasks, discarding the scores

RETURN tasks from most to least important

Understanding Questions & Answers
Q1: What happens with tied scores?
The code doesn't handle ties — two tasks with equal scores appear in their original list order. A real system might break ties by creation date.

Q2: What happens with an empty list?
It returns an empty list without crashing. Python handles empty lists gracefully in loops and sorting.

Q3: Why use _ instead of a real variable name?
The _ is a Python convention meaning 'I know this value exists but I deliberately don't need it.' It tells anyone reading the code: don't worry about this, it's intentionally being ignored.

Q4: What ONE word change makes lowest priority appear first?
# Change True to False
sorted(task_scores, key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=False)

Prompt 3: Complex Logic and Control Flow
Control Flow Diagram
Here is the complete decision path through calculate_task_score():

START → task comes in
  │
  ▼
Set base score (priority × 10)
  │
  ▼
Has due date? ──NO──→ skip, score unchanged
  │YES
  ▼
Calculate days_until_due
  ├── < 0?   YES → +35 (overdue)
  ├── == 0?  YES → +20 (due today)
  ├── <= 2?  YES → +15 (due very soon)
  ├── <= 7?  YES → +10 (due this week)
  └── > 7?       → +0  (plenty of time)
  │
  ▼
Status check
  ├── DONE?    YES → -50
  ├── REVIEW?  YES → -15
  └── other?       → +0
  │
  ▼
Has blocker/critical/urgent tag? YES → +8
  │
  ▼
Updated today? YES → +5
  │
  ▼
RETURN final score

Why Condition Order Matters
The due date conditions must be checked from most urgent to least urgent. If <= 7 was checked first, an overdue task would match it and only get +10 instead of +35 — completely wrong!

Potential Logic Bugs Discovered
Bug	Description
No score cap	A task could theoretically score very high with the right combination
DONE tasks still visible	URGENT + DONE = 10 points — still positive, could appear in top 5
Case sensitive tags	'Blocker' would NOT match 'blocker' — must be exact lowercase
Days vs hours	Updated 23 hours ago counts as 0 days and gets the +5 bonus

Scenario Predictions & Answers
Scenario 1: MEDIUM, no due date, TODO, no tags, updated 3 days ago
20 (medium) + 0 (no due date) + 0 (todo) + 0 (no tags) + 0 (3 days ago) = 20 points

Scenario 2: LOW, overdue, DONE, tagged 'blocker'
10 (low) + 35 (overdue) - 50 (done) + 8 (blocker) + 0 = 3 points
Very low despite being overdue — DONE's -50 penalty wipes out almost everything else. Intentional design.

Scenario 3: HIGH, due in exactly 7 days, REVIEW, updated today
40 (high) + 10 (<=7 days) - 15 (review) + 0 (no tags) + 5 (today) = 40 points

Key Insights & Learning Points
•	Weighted scoring is more powerful than single-factor sorting — it balances WHAT a task is with WHEN it needs doing
•	The order of elif conditions is critical — checking most urgent first prevents wrong scores
•	The -50 DONE penalty is a deliberate design choice to hide completed work from active views
•	The Decorate-Sort-Undecorate pattern is a reusable technique for sorting objects by calculated values
•	any() is efficient — it stops at the first match rather than checking every tag
•	Using _ as a variable name is a Python convention meaning 'intentionally ignored'
•	The algorithm has gaps: no tie-breaking, case-sensitive tags, and no score cap

